        Chart Review 06/09/24

        I'M IN COLLEGE AGAIN FOLKS.

        Yes, year two of my grand scheme to take over my local area has come to fruition and I must say, we've had a grand summer, haven't we? The Euros were great except if you're from Croatia, the Olympics/Paralympics have been pretty fun if you ignore Twitter, and of course, there's been loads of fresh and exciting talent to throw their weight around in the music scene of late. We can talk about Charli XCX all we want, but there was also Eminem remembering how to be relevant, Glastonbury trying to prove that LCD Soundsystem and PJ Harvey are good enough to prelude Dua Lipa on the Main Stage, Deadpool & Wolverine somehow causing 2000's finest to impact the charts, Chase & Status slapping everyone about, and brilliant albums from beabadoobee, Bring Me The Horizon, Twenty One Pilots, SOFT PLAY, and Fontaines D.C.. Oh, and a certain Teenage Witch has become inescapable since the warm weather kicked in. But you knew that already.

        Anyways, it's a fresh new season now, and yesterday saw two fun events happen. Not only did San Marino finally win a football match (I wasn't even ALIVE the last time they were victorious), but the Mercury Prize happened as well. It was alright, wasn't it? Forget about the fact that there's no sponsor now, and none of the acts got to perform live, and the ceremony is basically on it's deathbed at this point. No one wants to know about those trivial matters, Instead, we should be praising the lord that such innovative and fantastic sounds eminated from the cream bun of this year's festivities. Not that This Could Be Texas by Leeds indie-The Fall wannabes English Teacher is THAT much of a culture shock, but you know, at least it wasn't Cat Burns.

        Moving on from that though, and the charts are dead. Again. WHY. Can't there just be a double-ACR trigger for artists like Benson Boone and Noah Kahan who've been lurking around since JANUARY? I could do without hearing Stick Season for another 6 months, thanks. There's only 1 new hit and 1 re-entry today (congrats to The Kid LAROI I guess, even if NIGHTS LIKE THIS still makes me promptly ignore it), and that new hit is hardly the kind that will make us stare into the sky and shout "WE LOVE POP". Speaking of which...

        Sabrina Carpenter is unstoppable right now. She is basically the Justin Bieber of the mid-2020s right now. Everything she touches turns to gold so much it's ridiculous. Just like last week, she holds a monopoly of the Top 3 spots, with Taste marking Week Number 2 at the summit, meanwhile Please Please Please and Espresso continue to guffaw even the most obsessive fangirl on the planet. So yeah, she's still the queen of pop right now. Except in the album chart, because she's been kicked down to No.2. Why? Well, you know. Oasis are back. Kind of.

        Yeah, no, you couldn't make it up. 15 years after Liam and Noel Gallagher promptly sacked off working with each other any longer, they're finally back to do one of those reunion tours you do when your bank balance is slimming too much. And it did some funny things to the chart last week in ways I couldn't really fathom. OK, so they've all dropped off on Spotify this week, but that hasn't stopped their trio of classics budging up the chart and making everyone feel uncomfortable. Charging it's way to 8 is 1994 hit Live Forever, whose former No.10 peak is now forever lost to time eternal. Joining it in the best-sellers just behind it is 1996 chart-topper Don't Look Back In Anger, with '95 (only) American smash and busker's anthem Wonderwall down at 11. Oh yeah, and it's been 30 years since Definitely Maybe happened so they re-released it and watched the money roll in. Poor Nick Cave & The Bad Seeds man. I'm just glad they squeeked into the Top 5.

        So as Dasha finally falls out of the Top 10 after like, 5 months, and Gigi Perez and Gracie Abrams crawl up the listings in convincing fashion, it's time to celebrate the only new entry. Except it's not much cop. Considering feelslikeimfallinginlove is still throwing it's beige shapes around the Top 40, it feels wrong for Coldplay to shove their second single from Moon Music out on an unwilling public. And it looked like it too, because it flopped at 44 last week. Similar situations were about to happen this week until the inevitable and completely worthless PHYSICAL RELEASE, a move that always makes me throw my remote at the TV screen in frustration. So yeah, WE PRAY is at 31 now. Little Simz and Burna Boy are on here, but they're not credited for some bizarre circumstance that I will not bother decoding, so I'll just leave it at that. Also, second singles from Coldplay albums usually do extraordinarily well. Yellow, The Scientist, Fix You, Viva La Vida, Paradise, A Sky Full Of Stars, Hymn For The Weekend and My Universe have all been massive. WE PRAY just sounds like album filler.

        Outside the chart and Addison Rae has risen to 50 in short order so expect the Lana Del Rey impersonator to infect your craniums with haste. 360 by Charli XCX tumbles to 69 because it's on ACR, Becky Hill's latest flog has limped to 73, Drake and The Kid LAROI are back with songs I completely forgot about until I started this write-up, K-Poppers LE SSERAFIM make their first chart bow, meanwhile another Fontaines D.C. album track pops up along with the usual new dance drivel that has also debuted. And I know that because Breaking Me by Topic was AWFUL, and I despise anything he's involved in.

        Anyways, next week's chart will at least have SOME things going on next time, with Fred Again.. battling against David Gilmour for album supremacy. There's also an album where the likes of Simple Plan and Bowling For Soup cover Disney songs, but we don't need to worry about that, do we? In the singles market, Megan Thee Stallion ruins her reputation by hanging out with a BTS member, Linkin Park hire a woman to sing their new songs for absolutely no reason at all (but their new one's OK I guess), Halsey and Jungle return to underperform as always, David Guetta urinates all over Infinity by Guru Josh, and Central Cee has dragged in RAYE for his new one and then ditches her after 40 seconds. Go figure. BYE.
